result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:18 pm Def in court w/ Atty Patricia L. O'Neil.  Def in custody.  Emily E. Hynek appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

3:11 pm Def in court w/ Atty Patricia L. O'Neil.  Def in custody.  Stephanie R. Hilton appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
FTA at the 11/25/14 plea hrg.  PO has an apprehension request on her.  O'Neil:  Kiara was at Ophelia's house for a length of time.  It's pretty clear, however, that at some point she used drugs.  She was working with JS but absconded.  She went to L. E Phillips for detox.  Judge Levine put out the apprehension request.  Her mother than brought her here.  COURT:  She turned herself into L. E. Phillips?  O'Neil:  Yes.  Kiesow says she was scared to come to court when she relapsed.  Went to detox 2 days later.  Was in L. E. Phillips for 7 days.  I spent a day with my mom and then turned myself in.  O'Neil states she's made progress...  She continue to be on probation.  Kiesow states she was doing very well until a group of girls came into Ophelia's House.  This time I was able to come back; went to detox and turned myself in.  I want to get out of La Crosse  Co. to Amber, Wis. where my mom is.  COURT:  I don't know if I can trust her in the community.  O'Neil:  As of Nov. 5th,, the was not yet transitioned out of Ophelia's house.  COURT:  The only benefit for her is to leave her in jail until the plea is done and then transfer her to Amber, Wis.  Kiesow states she doesn't want to leave this jail until she's transferred to Marianette Co.
COURT will leave the cash bonds as is.
